[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-baltimore-terrapins-season] The 1914 Baltimore Terrapins season was a season in American baseball.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-baltimore-terrapins-season] They finished in third place in the Federal League, 4½ games behind the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The **1914 Boston Braves season** was the 44th season of the franchise.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The team finished first in the National League, winning the pennant by 10½ games over the New York Giants after being in last place in the NL at midseason.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The team, which became known as the **1914 Miracle Braves**, went on to sweep the Philadelphia Athletics in the World Series.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The Braves performed one of the most memorable reversals in major league history, going from last place to first place in two months, becoming the first team to win a pennant after being in last place on the Fourth of July.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-braves-season] After finishing in fifth place in 1913 with a record of 69 wins and 82 losses, the Braves were not expected to be contenders.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-braves-season] They spent the first part of the season in last place, posting a record of 26 wins and 40 losses in early July.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-braves-season] Led by three pitchers, Dick Rudolph, Bill James, and Lefty Tyler, the team began to win games, taking over first place for good on September 8.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-braves-season] Their record over their final 87 games was 68–19 for a winning percentage of .782.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-braves-season] Infielders Johnny Evers and Rabbit Maranville led the league in double plays.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The Braves went on to sweep Connie Mack's heavily favored Athletics in four games in the 1914 World Series.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The team became known as the "Miracle" Braves and remain one of the most storied comeback teams in baseball history.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The franchise would not win another pennant until 1948.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-red-sox-season] The **1914 Boston Red Sox season** was the 14th season in the franchise's Major League Baseball history.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox finished second in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 62 losses, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1914-buffalo-buffeds-season/1914-boston-red-sox-season] The team played its home games at Fenway Park.
